{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-27",
    "title": "Academic Brevity: Participle Clauses",
    "description": "Learning how to join two sentences to sound shorter and more sophisticated (Having finished...).",
    "display_order": 27,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-26"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# Academic Brevity: Participle Clauses\n\nIn academic writing, we want to save space and sound sophisticated. We can join two sentences together using **Participle Clauses** when both sentences have the **same subject**.\n\n### 1. After something is finished: \"Having + V3\"\nUse this to show that the first action was completed before the second action began.\n- **Two Sentences**: The researcher finished the test. He wrote the report.\n- **Combined**: **Having finished** the test, the researcher wrote the report.\n\n### 2. At the same time: \"V-ing\"\nUse the \"ing\" form to show that the two actions happened at the same time.\n- **Two Sentences**: The student walked to the library. He thought about his exam.\n- **Combined**: **Walking** to the library, the student thought about his exam.\n\n### 3. Reason: \"V-ing\"\nYou can also use it to show the **reason** for the next action.\n- **Two Sentences**: I felt sick. I decided not to attend the lecture.\n- **Combined**: **Feeling** sick, I decided not to attend the lecture. (Because I felt sick...)\n\n### 4. Critical Note\nThe subject of both parts **MUST** be the same! \n- **Incorrect**: \"Having finished the test, the report was written by me.\" (The report didn't finish the test!)\n- **Correct**: \"Having finished the test, I wrote the report.\"\n\n---",
